        Pink sunset
    </h1>

    <!-- Replace date -->
    <p class="post-date">
        May, 2026
    </p>

  	<img src="pinksunset.jpg" alt="pink sunset in Hawaii">
    
    <article style="margin-top: 40px;" class="essay">

        <p>Surfing used to take up such a big part of my life. after a sudden injury, not only surfing but even the things i loved, exercising, or simple daily tasks like grocery shopping became difficult. There were many days when i felt helpless and stayed in bed for hours. 
		</p>
		<p>So i started this 30-day challenge as a way to plant a small seed of motivation in myself every day. 
		</p>
		
		<div class="photo-row">
		 <img src="30chal_stin.JPG" alt="30day challenge stinray">
  	  	 <img src="30chal_fire.JPG" alt="30day challenge woodfire">
		</div>

		<p style="margin-top: 10px;">Actually, it wasn't easy. Even though the paintings were small A4 size, I thought about what to draw every day, completed them, filmed the process, made a video, and uploaded it. For 30 days. It was a lot of work. As the 30th approached, I was amazed at how much I had actually accomplished. Considering the past few months spent lying in bed, it was a tremendous sense of achievement. I was truly proud of myself.
		</p>
		<p>No dramatic change after the 30-day challenge. Life just went back to normal.  I still want to paint but starting again feels hard. That daily pressure, finishing one piece every 24 hours, actually helped more than I thought. I even thought about doing 100 days, but instead I feel drawn to something bigger. So my next challenge would be a large painting. 
		</p>
		<p>Maybe one day, my work will hang on a white wall like one at the local gallery.
		</p>


    </article>

